{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568240"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:11:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:11:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19676"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19676"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.82,0.02,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114695"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12451"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96698"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2287"},{"type":"tags","id":"2479"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48133"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114695"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her annual health check. She has hypertension and osteoarthritis but is otherwise well. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. She received her influenza vaccine two months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe enquires about the new respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) vaccine after seeing an advertisement and she is interested in learning about whether it may be recommended for her. She has no history of chronic lung disease, heart disease, or immunocompromise.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate recommendation regarding RSV vaccination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vaccination is contraindicated due to recent influenza vaccination","Vaccination can be considered after discussion of benefits, risks and cost","Vaccination should be deferred until RSV season","Vaccination should be deferred until age 75","Vaccination is only recommended if she develops chronic lung disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case addresses the recommendations for RSV vaccination in older adults. According to current Australian guidelines, RSV vaccination is recommended for:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPregnant women to protect their newborn infant;\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll people aged \u226575 years;\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people aged \u226560 years; and\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeople with medical risk factors for severe RSV disease aged \u226560 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-Indigenous adults aged 60\u201374 years (such as this patient) who do not have a medical risk factor for severe RSV disease may \u003Cstrong\u003Econsider\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination (Note: the wording in the Australian Immunisation Handbook is that they may \u0022consider\u0022 vaccination as opposed to those over \u226575 being \u0022recommended\u0022 vaccination). Those in this age group have a lower risk of severe RSV disease than people aged \u226575 years, so the benefit of vaccination may be less.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical risks factors for severe RSV disease can be viewed at the Australian Immunisation Handbook, referring to the table \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003EConditions associated with increased risk of severe RSV disease in adults\u0027.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe RSV vaccine (Abrysvo) is funded on the National Immunisation Program for pregnant women between 28-36 weeks gestation to protect their newborn infants from severe RSV disease. The vaccine is available on private prescription at a cost of approximately $300 for older adults, with some states and territories offering subsidised vaccination to those in other groups not included above. Protection lasts for 2 years - the need for further doses has not been established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination can be considered after discussion of benefits, risks and cost\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option. While the benefits may be greater in those \u226575 years or those with risk factors, vaccination can still be offered to this patient after discussing individual circumstances including the significant out-of-pocket cost.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination should be deferred until age 75\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the recommendations are stronger for those \u226575 years, there is no need to wait if the patient wishes to receive the vaccine, after discussion of the benefits, risks, and cost.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination is contraindicated due to recent influenza vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. RSV vaccine can be safely co-administered with other vaccines, including influenza vaccine, with no waiting period required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination should be deferred until RSV season\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While ideally given before RSV season (winter in Australia), the vaccine can be administered at any time of the year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination is only recommended if she develops chronic lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While chronic lung disease is a risk factor for severe RSV disease, the vaccine can be given to adults aged 60 years and over, regardless of comorbidities, following discussion of the benefits, risks, and costs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-Indigenous adults aged 60\u201374 years who do not have a medical risk factor for severe RSV disease may consider vaccination, but there is a stronger recommendation for those aged 75 years and over.","RSV vaccine can be co-administered with other vaccines including influenza vaccine.","RSV vaccination can be given at any time of year but is ideally administered before RSV season (winter).","RSV vaccine costs approximately $300 for older adults and is not currently subsidised on the PBS.","RSV vaccine (Abrysvo) is funded on the National Immunisation Program for pregnant women between 28-36 weeks gestation to protect their newborn infant."],"references":["Australian Immunisation Handbook. Australian Government: Department of Health and Aged Care. Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv#recommendations"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96698"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19676"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96698"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T20:31:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T20:32:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12451"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114695"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":